Pretty little church ‚õ™Ô∏è located in the heart of the pleasant and family-friendly Batignoles district. This church, located on the axis of rue des Batignolles, has the appearance of a Greek temple. Its triangular pediment is supported by four Tuscan-style columns. His pulpit, through its rich symbolism, shows how the Word of God acts. Its stained glass windows depict the life of Mary. A small bell tower houses a bell called ‚Äú√âtiennette‚Äù which, since 1857, has punctuated the hours of our neighborhood which has retained the charm of a large village.
Not a fan of Catholic places of worship, but there for a classical concert. Good acoustics.
A beautiful church with a dynamic priest who is very pleasant to listen to. A beautiful place of worship to attend a mass or to visit. The organ and its master offer pleasant sounds. To recommend.
Very active parish. The church is pretty and well located. On a square and opposite a very pleasant park where many birds live.
A pretty church that fits well into the neighborhood. The stained glass windows and the heart are beautiful.

Construction of the Sainte-Marie church began in 1828, under the direction of architect¬†Jacques Molinos thanks to donations from¬†Charles X and the¬†Duchess of Angoul√™me. The church took its name from Sainte-Marie des¬†Batignolles¬†in 1830 when Charles X created the new commune of¬†Batignolles-Monceau by separating it from the commune of¬†Clichy-la-Garenne. In 1839, with the population growing, it was decided to enlarge the small church, despite the previous enlargement of 1834. As a result, the architect¬†Paul-Eug√®ne Lequeux (who would build the district's town hall) decided to add two chapels laterally. On April 2, 1841, the archbishop, Mgr Affre, blessed the statue of the Virgin and consecrated the two altars dedicated to the Virgin Mary and Saint Vincent de Paul. Legend has it that a worker found a statuette of the Virgin during the foundation work. But it is safer to stick to the will of the Duchess of Angoul√™me who had wanted the dedication of the new church to be made to her patron saint, Marie de Nazareth.  To be discovered with curiosity just like the neighborhood.

A good church, very beautiful and quite well located. It is therefore not the building itself that poses a problem, but rather the attendance. Only bobos who just come to give themselves a good image. Sunday morning mass is a daycare, with children from everywhere who prevent us from following mass because they are so noisy. Some services are a little too festive and not spiritual enough. Otherwise the priests are not bad, but the church suffers from frequenting facade Catholics.

Beautiful facade inspired by Greek temples. The interior isn't bad too. It's worth it to pray, not too many people so you can be peaceful. Even if you just relax for 5 minutes, you're calm. But if we want to say that we saw a Parthenon in miniature, we can cite this church.üòÇ‚úå ‚Ä¶

Beautiful neoclassical church from the 19th century located in the heart of the village of Batignolles, next to the square of the same name, convenient for taking beautiful photos after baptisms, communions or weddings. It is one of the rare churches that does not have a bell tower, although you can still hear the bells. This does not harm its aesthetic because its four large white columns give it the air of a Greek temple. The interior is not huge but its choir and organ are magnificent.
Beautiful, well-maintained church located in a pretty square, however a clean-looking colored crook was persistently begging.

It is not possible to say "I loved it" for a parish, hence 4 stars and not 5...  A big thank you to the parish of Ste Marie des Batignolles which accepted that the farewell mass of my sister Florence took place in this church in accordance with her wishes, even though it was not her home parish. A big thank you also to the reception and support teams for the grieving families who were very warm and very efficient.
